    "body": "### Problem\n\n- Severity: `Medium`\n- Affected locations:\n  - `runtime/autoload/provider/clipboard.vim:53`\n  - `runtime/autoload/provider/clipboard.vim:242`\n- Trigger points:\n  - `system(a:cmd)` inside `s:cmd_ok(cmd)`\n  - `executable('xsel') && s:cmd_ok('xsel -o -b')` in `provider#clipboard#Executable()`\n\nWhen detecting whether to use `xsel`, the clipboard provider first checks `executable('xsel')` and then immediately executes `xsel -o -b`. There is no filtering for executable files located in the current directory.\n\nTherefore, as long as the graphical environment conditions are met (e.g., `DISPLAY` is set), and a malicious `xsel` exists in the current directory or a directory that takes precedence in `PATH`, the malicious program will be executed during the provider selection phase.\n\nThis issue has been verified to exist, but the prerequisite is that the local `PATH` is insecure or that a priority directory can be controlled by an attacker. This is not a remotely exploitable vulnerability by default, nor is it an issue that necessarily triggers on normal Neovim startup.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Create a temporary directory `/tmp/cwdhijack-clip`.  \n2. Write a malicious `xsel` script and grant it execute permissions.  \n3. Prepend the current directory to the `PATH`.  \n4. Set a non-empty `DISPLAY`, e.g., `DISPLAY=:1`.  \n5. Use headless Neovim to load `provider/clipboard.vim` and call `provider#clipboard#Executable()`.  \n6. Check whether `/tmp/cwdhijack-clip-fired` has been created.  \n\n```sh\nmkdir -p /tmp/cwdhijack-clip\n\ncat >/tmp/cwdhijack-clip/xsel <<'EOF'\n#!/bin/sh\necho Pwned >/tmp/cwdhijack-clip-fired\nexit 0\nEOF\n\nchmod +x /tmp/cwdhijack-clip/xsel\nrm -f /tmp/cwdhijack-clip-fired\n\ncd /tmp/cwdhijack-clip\nDISPLAY=:1 PATH=.:$PATH nvim --headless -u NONE \\\n  \"+runtime autoload/provider/clipboard.vim | echo provider#clipboard#Executable()\" +qall\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n### Impact\n\n- Executes an attacker-controlled local program with the current user's privileges.\n- The trigger condition is when the clipboard provider is loaded and enters the `xsel` auto-detection path.\n- The trigger surface is more environment-dependent compared to the node provider, making it more likely to be triggered in desktop Linux/WSL/X11 environments where `DISPLAY` is set.\n- A normal `nvim --headless -u NONE -i NONE +qall` startup does not appear to trigger this automatically.\n\n### Root Cause\n\n- The use of `system(a:cmd)` for probing does not validate the source of the executable.\n- This is inconsistent with the security policies already implemented in `gzip.vim` and `perl.vim`.\n\n### Remediation Suggestions\n\n- For `xsel` and other external tools that are executed directly during the probing phase, uniformly implement trusted path validation.\n- Only use absolute paths to execute tools that have passed validation.\n- Separate \"detection of availability\" from \"command execution\" to avoid running untrusted binaries during the probing phase.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.12.2\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nUbuntu 22.04\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nWSL2 + Windows Terminal\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nbuild from repo",
